SIMPLE: lose
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lose
<hw>Lose</hw> <pr>(l⟦oomac⟧z)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Lost</conjf> <pr>(l⟦ocr⟧st; 115)</pr> <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Losing</conjf>
<pr>(l⟦oomac⟧z"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>losien</ets> to
loose, be lost, lose, AS. <ets>losian</ets> to become loose; akin to OE.
<ets>leosen</ets> to lose, p. p. <ets>loren</ets>, <ets>lorn</ets>, AS.
<ets>le⟦iacute⟧san</ets>, <ets>p. p. loren</ets> (in comp.), D.
ver<ets>liezen</ets>, G. ver<ets>lieren</ets>, Dan. for<ets>lise</ets>,
Sw. f⟦oum⟧r<ets>lisa</ets>, f⟦oum⟧r<ets>lora</ets>, Goth.
fra<ets>liusan</ets>, also to E. <ets>loose</ets>, a & v., L.
<ets>luere</ets> to loose, Gr. <grk>ly`ein</grk>, Skr.
<ets>l⟦umac⟧</ets> to cut. ⟦root⟧127. Cf. <er>Analysis</er>,
<er>Palsy</er>, <er>Solve</er>, <er>Forlorn</er>, <er>Leasing</er>,
<er>Loose</er>, <er>Loss</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To part with unintentionally or unwillingly, as by
accident, misfortune, negligence, penalty, forfeit, etc.; to be deprived
of; <as>as, to <ex>lose</ex> money from one's purse or pocket, or in
business or gaming; to <ex>lose</ex> an arm or a leg by amputation; to
<ex>lose</ex> men in battle.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fair Venus wept the sad disaster⟦br⟧
Of having <qex>lost</qex> her favorite dove.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cease to have; to possess no longer; to suffer
diminution of; <as>as, to <ex>lose</ex> one's relish for anything; to
<ex>lose</ex> one's health.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the salt hath <qex>lost</qex> his savor, wherewith shall it be
salted?</q> <rj><qau>Matt. v. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Not to employ; to employ ineffectually; to throw
away; to waste; to squander; <as>as, to <ex>lose</ex> a day; to
<ex>lose</ex> the benefits of instruction.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The unhappy have but hours, and these they <qex>lose</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To wander from; to miss, so as not to be able to
and; to go astray from; <as>as, to <ex>lose</ex> one's
way</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He hath <qex>lost</qex> his fellows.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To ruin; to destroy; as destroy; <as>as, the ship
was <ex>lost</ex> on the ledge</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The woman that deliberates is <qex>lost</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To be deprived of the view of; to cease to see or
know the whereabouts of; <as>as, he <ex>lost</ex> his companion in the
crowd</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Like following life thro' creatures you dissect,⟦br⟧
You <qex>lose</qex> it in the moment you detect.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To fail to obtain or enjoy; to fail to gain or win;
hence, to fail to catch with the mind or senses; to miss; <as>as, I
<ex>lost</ex> a part of what he said</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He shall in no wise <qex>lose</qex> his reward.</q> <rj><qau>Matt.
x. 42.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I fought the battle bravely which I <qex>lost</qex>,⟦br⟧
And <qex>lost</qex> it but to Macedonians.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>To cause to part with; to deprive of.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How should you go about to <qex>lose</qex> him a wife he loves
with so much passion?</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>To prevent from gaining or obtaining.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O false heart! thou hadst almost betrayed me to eternal flames,
and <qex>lost</qex> me this glory.</q> <rj><qau>Baxter.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To lose ground</b></col>, <cd>to fall behind; to suffer
gradual loss or disadvantage.</cd> -- <col><b>To lose heart</b></col>,
<cd>to lose courage; to become timid.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧The mutineers
<xex>lost heart</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Macaulay.</au> -- <col><b>To lose
one's head</b></col>, <cd>to be thrown off one's balance; to lose the
use of one's good sense or judgment, through fear, anger, or other
emotion.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the excitement of such a discovery, many scholars <qex>lost
their heads</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Whitney.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>To lose one's self</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To forget
or mistake the bearing of surrounding objects; <as>as, <ex>to lose one's
self</ex> in a great city</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To have the
perceptive and rational power temporarily suspended; <as>as, we <ex>lose
ourselves</ex> in sleep</as>.</cd> -- <col><b>To lose sight
of</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To cease to see; <as>as, <ex>to lose
sight of</ex> the land</as>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To overlook; to
forget; to fail to perceive; <as>as, he <ex>lost sight of</ex> the
issue</as>.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lose</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Lose
<hw>Lose</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To suffer loss,
disadvantage, or defeat; to be worse off, esp. as the result of any kind
of contest.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We 'll . . . hear poor rogues⟦br⟧
Talk of court news; and we'll talk with them too,⟦br⟧
Who <qex>loses</qex> and who wins; who's in, who's out.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Losel</ent>⟦br⟧
